<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when serving white wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is serving white wine too cold, which mutes its aromatics and flavors. While many people default to "ice-cold" service, most white wines actually perform best between 45-50°F, allowing their complexity to shine through. Over-chilling can make even premium Chardonnays taste flat and one-dimensional.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I let white wine sit after opening before serving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most white wines benefit from 10-15 minutes of breathing after opening, particularly oak-aged Chardonnays and complex Rieslings. This brief aeration allows any reductive notes to blow off and helps the wine's aromatics develop. However, delicate wines like Muscadet or Vinho Verde should be served immediately to preserve their fresh, crisp character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant white wine, and if so, which types?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium aged white Burgundies, full-bodied Chardonnays, and mature Rieslings often benefit from decanting, especially if they show reductive aromas or have developed sediment. Young, crisp whites like Sauvignon Blanc or Pinot Grigio rarely need decanting and can actually lose their vibrant freshness. When decanting whites, use a smaller, narrower vessel and serve within 30 minutes to maintain optimal temperature.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between serving temperature for different white wine styles?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Light, crisp wines like Albariño and Vermentino shine at 40-45°F to emphasize their refreshing acidity, while full-bodied wines like oak-aged Chardonnay and white Rhône blends perform best at 50-55°F to showcase their complexity. Sweet wines like Sauternes should be served slightly colder at 43-46°F to balance their richness. Sparkling wines require the coldest service at 38-42°F to maintain proper effervescence and crispness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I quickly chill white wine if I forgot to refrigerate it?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most effective method is an ice bath with salt water, which can chill a bottle from room temperature to serving temperature in 15-20 minutes. Fill a bucket with equal parts ice and water, add a handful of salt to lower the freezing point, and fully submerge the bottle. Avoid the freezer, which can over-chill the wine and potentially cause the cork to push out or the bottle to crack.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What glassware makes the biggest difference for white wine service?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">A proper white wine glass with a smaller bowl than red wine glasses concentrates aromatics while maintaining cooler temperatures longer. For aromatic varieties like Gewürztraminer and Viognier, choose glasses with slightly wider bowls to capture their complex bouquet, while crisp wines like Chablis benefit from narrower, more upright bowls. Always hold the glass by the stem to prevent warming the wine with your hand.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I keep an opened bottle of white wine fresh?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most white wines maintain their quality for 3-5 days when properly stored in the refrigerator with a quality vacuum pump or inert gas system like Coravin. Aromatic wines like Sauvignon Blanc and Moscato are best consumed within 2-3 days as they lose their vibrant character quickly, while fuller-bodied wines like Chardonnay can maintain quality for up to a week. Always re-cork tightly and store upright to minimize oxygen contact.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is following sommelier serving techniques worth it for everyday wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely – proper serving temperature, glassware, and timing can elevate even a $15 bottle significantly by allowing its true character to emerge. Simple techniques like checking temperature with a wine thermometer and using appropriate glasses cost little but dramatically improve the drinking experience. Even basic wines show better balance, aromatics, and flavor complexity when served with attention to these fundamental principles.</p>
  </div>
